## Assigning an output value to elements of the XML file
This feature allows to define the assignment of an output value to any element in the XML Writer component's schema.

> Note

The output value is always a constant.

The functionality is useful, for example, when you want to mark with a constant the different XML Writers in a project to differentiate their output, as they represent different ways of sending the output file.

- Open the XML Writer's resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources.](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources)

-  Select the required element from the panel on the left.

- Select the **Values **tab on the right.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Select the **Output value assignment is enabled **option to enable the assignment of an output value to the selected item.

- In the **Value **text field, enter the output value to assign to the selected element. The schema panel displays the ![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) icon next to the selected item; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Include in output **section, select when to return the element:

**Always**

- **Only on some conditions**

> Note

For more information, see [Defining output conditions](#) below.

### Defining logical expressions for conditional output
This feature allows to define a logical expression to set the specific conditions for the XML Writer to return the element and its children in the output file.

In particular, it is possible to:

- Define variables.

- Correlate variables using a logical expression.

- Select the **Only on some conditions **option for the **Include in output **parameter. The **Output condition **panel is displayed.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Click **Add condition **to define a new variable. The variable is automatically added to the logical expression area.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Condition definition **section, click on the configuration fields in the row corresponding to a variable to configure it; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip

To remove a variable from the condition definition table, move your mouse pointer over the corresponding row and click ![](data:image/png;base64,) .

**Column**

**Description**

**Condition name**

Name of the variable

**Path**

Select the data schema field to use from the browsable tree.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Operator**

Select the required logical operator from the drop-down menu. The available options are:

**Operator**

**Description**

**=**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is equal to that defined by the user.

**!=**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is different from the one defined by the user.

**&gt;=**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is greater than or equal to that defined by the user.

**&lt;=**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is less than or equal to that defined by the user.

**&gt;**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is greater than that defined by the user.

**&lt;**

If the numeric value expressed by the string on the page is less than that defined by the user.

**contains**

If the string on the page contains the string defined by the user.

**start_with**

If the string on the page starts with the string defined by the user.

**ends_with**

If the string on the page ends with the string defined by the user.

**has_pattern**

If the string in the page matches the regular expression.

**has_changed**

If the string on the page is different from that on the previous page.

**has_changed_ignore_e mpty**

If the string on the page is different from the one on the previous page and it is not empty.

**is_empty**

If the string on the page is empty.

**not_empty**

If the string on the page is not empty.

**is_numeric**

If the string on the page is a numerical value.

**Value**

Enter the value to use to match the expression.

- *(optional) *In the **Condition configuration **section, concatenate conditions using boolean operators; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

In the logical expression area, select the required variable.

- Click the icon corresponding to the boolean operator that you want to apply:

**AND**

- **OR**

- **NOT**

- **(**

- **)**

> Note

Parentheses allow you to group variables and boolean operators in the logical expression.

> Tip

To delete a variable or a boolean operator from the logical expression area, move your mouse pointer over the corresponding placeholder and click ![](data:image/png;base64,) .

To add a variable to the logical expression, drag it from the condition definition table and drop it into the logical expression area.

Drag &amp; drop variables and boolean operators within the logical expression to rearrange them.

- Repeat steps 24 to define and correlate the required variables, using logical expressions to define the output condition for the selected element.

> Tip

Click the **CHECK** link on the bottom-right of the **Output conditions** panel to check the correctness of the logical expression. The system will perform a syntax check and displays a status message with the result; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)
